engrin, Arthur, and Buddha. Rank's monograph remains the classic application of Freudian theory to hero myths. In The Hero the noted English ethnologist Raglan singles out the myth-ritualist pattern in James Frazer's many-sided Golden Bough and applies that pattern to hero myths. Dundes, the eminent folklorist at the University of California at Berkeley, applies the theories of Rank, Raglan, and others to the case of Jesus. In his introduction to this selection from Rank, Raglan, and Dundes, Robert Segal, author of the major study of Joseph Campbell, charts the history of theorizing about hero myths and compares the approaches of Rank, Raglan, Dundes, and Campbell.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aHeroesxMythology. 0aHeroesxReligious aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh  aAarne–Thompson classification systems.  aAfrasiab.  aAlan Dundes.  aAlcmene.  aAmulius.  aArchetype.  aAreoi.  aAstyages.  aAttis.  aBiography.  aBooks of Kings.  aCarl Jung.  aCastor and Pollux.  aCastration.  aCombatant.  aConsciousness.  aConsummation.  aCounter-Reformation.  aCreation myth.  aCuckold.  aCulture hero.  aDhritarashtra.  aDirce.  aEtymology.  aEuhemerism.  aEunuch.  aEurystheus.  aFairy tale.  aFlood myth.  aGottfried von Strassburg.  aGrandparent.  aGreat King.  aGreek mythology.  aGwydion.  aHerder.  aHero Tales.  aHerodotus.  aHistorical Jesus.  aHistorical figure.  aHistoricity of Jesus.  aHistoricity.  aImportant People.  aIncest.  aJohn Badby.  aJustin Martyr.  aLaius.  aLegend.  aLegendary creature.  aLongus.  aMendicant.  aMenelaus.  aMorganatic marriage.  aMr.  aMyth and ritual.  aMyth.  aMythological Cycle.  aMythology.  aNarrative.  aNeurosis.  aNimrod.  aNumitor.  aOedipus c